DENGUE ERADICATION CAMPAIGN - BRAZIL (02)
=========================================
Date: Thu, 27 Feb 1997 13:16:27 GMT+0200
From: Alan Kemp <alank@niv.ac.za>
[see
Dengue eradication campaign - Brazil 970224123034]
[I apologize for the delay in posting this message. I sent it for posting
but somehow it was returned to me without having been posted. Another of
those great mysteries of life. -- Mod CHC]
Interesting combination, reading the two postings in ProMED-DIGEST v97.n051
about Brazil's campaign for the eradication of dengue (a temporary measure at
best, judging from history) and Tim Stephenson's definition of an epidemic.
Do I detect a dry wit or two, or have I got it wrong?
Did a senior public officer have to contract the disease before Brazil
decided to attempt the eradication of dengue by eradicating its vector?
Greater minds than mine are convinced that localized eradication of a mobile,
adaptable, highly succesful organism such as _Aedes aegypti_ is a waste of
time. If you can't eliminate this mosquito from the neighbouring
territories, you will run the risk of re-introduction - need we be reminded
that this has already occurred once before in this region of the world. In
fact, that may not even be sufficient as _aegypti_ is still quite capable of
inter-continental spread, whether by introduction of eggs and larvae in used
tyre casings traded between countries, or by the direct importation of adults
in sea-going vessels or aircraft.
Having said all that, something obviously has to be done about Brazil's
dengue epidemic and "source-reduction" (the eradication of _Aedes aegypti_
larval habitats) as espoused by CDC's Dr Duane Gubler (1989) and WHO's Dr
Norman Gratz (1991) amongst others, appears to be the only long-term answer
to keeping _aegypti_ at bay. In the short term, adulticide applications by
ULV may be required, even though ULV applications are notoriously inefficient
for reducing mosquito populations where a large proportion of the mosquitoes
rest inside houses.
References:
Gratz, NG (1991) Emergency control of _Aedes aegypti_ as a disease vector in
urban areas. J. Am. Mosq. Cntrl. Assoc. 7:353-365.
Gubler, DJ (1989) _Aedes aegypti_ and _Aedes aegypti_-borne disease control
in the 1990s: top down or bottom up. Am. J. trop. Med. Hyg. 40:571-578.
Hope this rehash of established comment is of some use.
