[Doesn't seem to me that any single method of reducing dengue vectors will
ever be successful. "Top down" or "bottom up" might both be useful, if
education is thrown into the formula. Governmental regulations and
neighborhood volunteers, source reduction, innovative vaccines, and other,
more novel means, will be required. We cannot wait for Ministers of Health
of all countries to get dengue before something is done on a global scale.
Perhaps campaigns to vaccinate everyone in at-risk areas against yellow fever
might provide sufficient immunity to the (very) heterologous dengue viruses
and reduce dengue viremias, thereby reducing the likelihood of transmission
of dengue viruses. I recall President Johnson (Lyndon, not Andrew) promising
"guns and butter" during the Vietnam War. One of the first things to go was
the Aedes Aegypti Eradication Program, after which the US began reexporting
these mosquitoes to areas of Latin America which had been free of them for
some years. Control of dengue will require the concerted effort of
innovative people in all countries at risk. The bottom line is that what has
been tried has not worked or, more likely, what has been suggested has not
been tried.
...........................................................................chc
